  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "When I record my face and the video I am reacting to on the same computer, the audio plays in the background of webcam footage. How do I fix it?",
  "response": "To avoid capturing background audio from the video you're reacting to while recording your webcam, you can use several methods depending on the software you're using for your recording. Here are a few solutions:\n\n### 1. **Use Separate Audio Channels**\n   - **Software**: If you're using software like OBS Studio, you can set different audio channels. \n   - **Steps**:\n     - Open OBS Studio and go to `Audio Mixer`.\n     - Right-click on the audio source that is capturing the video sound, and select `Filters`.\n     - Add a new filter: `Audio Monitor` or similar, and set it to Monitor Only.\n     - Make sure your microphone is routed to the main output only without headphone monitoring.\n\n### 2. **Choose Different Audio Input Sources**\n   - **Audio capture**: If your recording software allows, choose to only capture your microphone.\n   - **Steps**:\n     - In your recording software settings, look for audio input options.\n     - Select your microphone as the input and make sure the desktop audio (or the audio from the video) is disabled or muted.\n\n### 3. **Physical Setup**\n   - **Microphone Positioning**: Position your microphone closer to your face. \n   - **Speakers**: If you're using speakers to play the video, switch to headphones to avoid capturing the video audio.\n\n### 4. **Post-Production Editing**\n   - If you have already recorded the video with background audio:\n   - Use video editing software (like DaVinci Resolve, Adobe Premiere Pro, or a simpler option like iMovie) to remove or mute the audio track from the video and keep only your commentary.\n\n### 5. **Use Virtual Audio Cables**\n   - **Setup**: Virtual audio cable software can help separate the audio streams on your computer.\n   - **Steps**:\n     - Download and install virtual audio cable software (like VB-Audio Virtual Cable).\n     - Set the output of the video software to the virtual audio cable and input your recording software to use your microphone instead.\n\n### 6. **Video Capture Software Options**\n   - **Specific Software Settings**: Some video capturing software includes a built-in feature to separate or isolate audio inputs.\n   - **Steps**: Check the documentation or support for the specific software you are using to see if such features exist.\n\n### 7. **Adjusting the Video's Playback Environment**\n   - If applicable, play the video on another device (like a phone or tablet) while recording your reaction. This way, you ensure that the video audio is not captured at all while recording your face.\n\nBy applying one or more of these solutions, you should be able to eliminate the background audio from the video you're reacting to, resulting in a cleaner recording.",
